CSS Selectors
Selectors are used to target HTML elements that you want to style. There are several types of selectors in CSS.

Common Selectors
*: Universal selector
element: Type selector (e.g., p, h1)
#id: ID selector
.class: Class selector
element element: Descendant selector
element > element: Child selector
element + element: Adjacent sibling selector
element ~ element: General sibling selector
CSS Properties
CSS properties are used to define the styles that will be applied to the selected elements. There are many properties available in CSS.

Common Properties
color: Sets the color of text
background-color: Sets the background color of an element
font-family: Sets the font of text
font-size: Sets the size of text
margin: Sets the space outside an element
padding: Sets the space inside an element
border: Sets the border around an element
width: Sets the width of an element
height: Sets the height of an element
CSS Box Model
The CSS box model describes the rectangular boxes that are generated for elements in the document tree and how their dimensions and margins, borders, and padding are calculated.

Box Model Components
content: The content of the box, where text and images appear
padding: Clears an area around the content
border: A border that goes around the padding and content
margin: Clears an area outside the border

CSS Layout
CSS provides several layout techniques to control the position and size of elements.

Common Layout Techniques
display: Controls the display behavior of an element (block, inline, flex, grid, etc.)
position: Controls the positioning of an element (static, relative, absolute, fixed, sticky)
float: Floats an element to the left or right
flexbox: A layout model for arranging elements in a flexible way
grid: A layout model for creating complex grid-based layouts
